<code>sun.misc<\/code> optional (<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/google/gson/issues/1993\">#1993<\/a>).<\/li>\n<li>Deprecate <code>Gson.excluder()<\/code> exposing internal href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/google/gson/issues/1390\">#1390<\/a>).<\/li>\n<li>Better behaviour with Java 9+ and <code>Unsafe<\/code> if there is a security manager (<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/google/gson/issues/1712\">#1712<\/a>).<\/li>\n<li><code>EnumTypeAdapter<\/code> now works better when ProGuard has obfuscated enum fields (<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/google/gson/issues/1495\">#1495<\/a>).<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h2>Version 2.8.7<\/h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Fixed <code>ISO8601UtilsTest<\/code> failing on systems with UTC+X.<\/li>\n<li>Improved javadoc for <code>JsonStreamParser<\/code>.<\/li>\n<li>Updated proguard.cfg (<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/google/gson/issues/1693\">#1693<\/a>).<\/li>\n<li>Fixed <code>IllegalStateException<\/code> in <code>JsonTreeWriter<\/code> (<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/google/gson/issues/1592\">#1592<\/a>).<\/li>\n<li>Added <code>JsonArray.isEmpty()<\/code> (<a href=\"https://github-redirect.dependabot.com/google/gson/issues/1603\">#1603<\/a>).<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h2>Version 2.8.6<\/h2>\n<p><em>2019-10-04<\/em>  <a {"id":1248428802,"created_at":"2022-05-25T17:26:01Z","updated_at":"2022-05-25T20:46:46Z","state":"open","title":"HeatMap: Why ColorMapping enum?","html_url":"https://github.com/HanSolo/charts/issues/77","body":"To customize color of heatmap it has property typed as `ColorMapping` which represented by `enum`. And it has only method which is getter for JavaFX Built-in `javafx.scene.paint.LinearGradient`. So why can't you just use `LinearGradient`-property to set colors in `HeatMap`? Enums are final so that it is impossible to set custom `ColorMapping`. Extracting an interface from `ColorMapping` might be the solution which won't break existing code that much.\r\n\r\nSame for `AreaHeatMap`"}

{"id":865386118,"created_at":"2021-04-22T19:22:16Z","updated_at":"2022-05-03T16:59:38Z","state":"open","title":"JavaFX classpath vs. module path， \"Unsupported JavaFX configuration\"","html_url":"https://github.com/ControlSystemStudio/phoebus/issues/1882","body":"Since JDK 9, JavaFX is meant to be loaded from the module path. It \"works\" when adding it to the classpath, but according to https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8256362 that is not supported, and with JavaFX 16 there is now a warning on startup:\r\n```\r\nWARNING [javafx] Unsupported JavaFX configuration: classes were loaded from 'unnamed module @4809244d'\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe fix is to move all the javafx-*.jar files from the classpath onto the module path.\r\n\r\nDuring development with Eclipse that can be done in the 'Dependencies' tab of the Run Configuration. Remove all javafx-*.jar from the \"Classpath entries' and instead list them under the \"Modulepath Entries\". In addition, \"Add modules:\" at the bottom needs to be changed from the default \"--\" to \"ALL-MODULE-PATH\".\r\n\r\n![Screen Shot 2021-04-22 at 3 09 58 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1932421/115772189-d208db00-a37c-11eb-9e6d-fc7cd3da9aa3.png)\r\n\r\nUnclear what the easiest way is to remove the warning from the phoebus product.\r\nAdd `--module-path` options for the modular javafx jars to the launch script?\r\nTurn everything into modules? "}

I know it means a lot of effort to achieve that and this probably an excessive request. I just want to know how you think about it or what's your planning.\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you want to know why I suggest this, here are the reasons that I can think up:\r\n1. Modern UI than Swing/AWT and easy to customize. \r\n2. Less code and easier to maintain.\r\n3. Since Swing/AWT was deprecated, remaining bugs and new bugs won't be fixed.\r\n4. Compatible with Swing which means not everything needs to be rebuilded. \r\n5. Easier to accomplish some advanced features like Dark Mode theme(may be I guess).\r\n\r\nSince I use SciaReto as a personal knowledge base, I use it almost everyday, it is really a very good and useful tool, I'd like to see it becomes better and better.\r\n\r\nThanks"}

{"id":1054807251,"created_at":"2021-11-16T12:12:43Z","updated_at":"2022-05-21T22:00:30Z","state":"open","title":"Support building and running on Apple M1 Silicon","html_url":"https://github.com/bisq-network/bisq/pull/5835","body":"## Summary\r\n\r\nProblem: Prior to this commit, it was not possible to build or run (from source) the desktop app on Apple's M1 (macos aarch64) architecture.\r\n\r\nSolution: This commit makes all the changes necessary to successfully build and run on M1, but some of these changes require depending on snapshots and forks of certain dependencies, so this commit shouldn't be merged to master until those fixes are officially released. The changes made here include:\r\n\r\n1. Upgrading from JavaFX 16 to JavaFX 17. JavaFX 17 was the first release to support aarch64 binaries, and so it's required.\r\n\r\n2. Upgrading to a version of the openjfx-gradle-plugin that contains the fix at openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin#113 to download the correct aarch64-classified JavaFX 17 jars. NOTE: at the time of this commit, the fix has not been released, so we are now depending on a locally-built SNAPSHOT resolved from `mavenLocal()`.\r\n\r\n3. Upgrading to a version of the JFoenix library that includes a fix for the bug documented at sshahine/JFoenix#1187. At the time of this commit, this fix has only been published in the 'rationalityfrontline' fork of JFoenix, and so we've temporarily updated our dependency to point to that artifact. It appears that a new version of JFoenix is being developed that will contain this fix, but it hasn't shipped yet.\r\n\r\n## Notes\r\n\r\n - Gradle dependency verification metadata has been updated to reflect the changes mentioned above, but will need further updates to capture the Linux, Windows and MacOS Intel variants of the JavaFX 17 binaries.\r\n\r\n - Building and testing has been verified to work on JDKs 11 through 17, however:\r\n\r\n - Running the desktop app only works on JDKs 11 through 15 until sshahine/JFoenix#1205 is fixed. Right now, attempting to run on JDK 16+ will result in a `Cannot invoke \"javafx.scene.Node.getLayoutBounds()\" because \"this.textNode\" is null` error. See the above mentioned issue for details.\r\n\r\n - It was necessary to bump the minimum supported source compatibility in the Gradle build from Java 10 to Java 11 in order to be able to consume the upgraded JFoenix artifact.\r\n\r\n - ~~This PR builds on top of the #5824 and assumes it will be merged; only the latest commit in this PR (98dc483c10) should be considered by reviewers.~~ (no longer relevant after rebase and force-push)\r\n\r\n## TODO\r\n\r\n(what remains in order to take this PR out of draft, review and merge it)\r\n\r\n- [ ] sshahine/JFoenix#1205 to be fixed, released and upgraded to\r\n- [x] openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin#113 to be released and upgraded to\r\n- [ ] JavaFX 17 verification metadata to be updated for Linux, Windows and MacOS Intel architectures\r\n"}

{"id":1236561796,"created_at":"2022-05-16T03:20:21Z","updated_at":"2022-05-23T14:09:22Z","state":"open","title":"In RichTextFX 0.10.9， calling the `scrollToPixel` method on a CodeArea constructed in a background thread has no effect","html_url":"https://github.com/FXMisc/RichTextFX/issues/1110","body":"Here is an example:\r\n\r\n```java\r\nimport javafx.application.Application;\r\nimport javafx.application.Platform;\r\nimport javafx.scene.Scene;\r\nimport javafx.scene.layout.StackPane;\r\nimport javafx.stage.Stage;\r\nimport org.fxmisc.flowless.VirtualizedScrollPane;\r\nimport org.fxmisc.richtext.CodeArea;\r\n\r\npublic class Main extends Application {\r\n    @Override\r\n    public void start(Stage primaryStage) throws Exception {\r\n        StackPane root = new StackPane();\r\n        Scene scene = new Scene(root, 200, 400);\r\n        primaryStage.setScene(scene);\r\n\r\n        new Thread(() -> {\r\n            CodeArea area = new CodeArea();\r\n            area.replaceText(\"This is test text\\n\".repeat(10000));\r\n            area.scrollToPixel(0, 0);\r\n            Platform.runLater(() -> {\r\n                root.getChildren().add(new VirtualizedScrollPane<>(area));\r\n            });\r\n        }).start();\r\n\r\n        primaryStage.show();\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nIn RichTextFX 0.10.8, it open the `CodeArea` with the scroll bar at the top. But after updating to 0.10.9, it open the `CodeArea` with the scroll bar at the bottom.\r\n\r\nIn 0.10.9, I tried a lot of methods, but I can't create the `CodeArea` with the focus on the top in the background thread (`CodeArea`'s constructor that accepts `String` will also be at the bottom, both `selectRange` and `scrollToPixel` are invalid). The only way is to call `replaceText` on the JavaFX thread, but this will cause the screen to freeze."}

In contrast version 1.2.1 doesn't specify any dependencies. \r\n\r\n**Reproduces how often:** always\r\n\r\n### System Information (please complete the following information):\r\n - OS: Arch Linux\r\n - Java Version: OpenJDK 18\r\n - Version: 1.2.2\r\n - Maven 3.8.4\r\n"}

{"id":1248428802,"created_at":"2022-05-25T17:26:01Z","updated_at":"2022-05-25T20:46:46Z","state":"open","title":"HeatMap: Why ColorMapping enum?","html_url":"https://github.com/HanSolo/charts/issues/77","body":"To customize color of heatmap it has property typed as `ColorMapping` which represented by `enum`. And it has only method which is getter for JavaFX Built-in `javafx.scene.paint.LinearGradient`. So why can't you just use `LinearGradient`-property to set colors in `HeatMap`? Enums are final so that it is impossible to set custom `ColorMapping`. Extracting an interface from `ColorMapping` might be the solution which won't break existing code that much.\r\n\r\nSame for `AreaHeatMap`"}

{"id":865386118,"created_at":"2021-04-22T19:22:16Z","updated_at":"2022-05-03T16:59:38Z","state":"open","title":"JavaFX classpath vs. module path， \"Unsupported JavaFX configuration\"","html_url":"https://github.com/ControlSystemStudio/phoebus/issues/1882","body":"Since JDK 9, JavaFX is meant to be loaded from the module path. It \"works\" when adding it to the classpath, but according to https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8256362 that is not supported, and with JavaFX 16 there is now a warning on startup:\r\n```\r\nWARNING [javafx] Unsupported JavaFX configuration: classes were loaded from 'unnamed module @4809244d'\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe fix is to move all the javafx-*.jar files from the classpath onto the module path.\r\n\r\nDuring development with Eclipse that can be done in the 'Dependencies' tab of the Run Configuration. Remove all javafx-*.jar from the \"Classpath entries' and instead list them under the \"Modulepath Entries\". In addition, \"Add modules:\" at the bottom needs to be changed from the default \"--\" to \"ALL-MODULE-PATH\".\r\n\r\n![Screen Shot 2021-04-22 at 3 09 58 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1932421/115772189-d208db00-a37c-11eb-9e6d-fc7cd3da9aa3.png)\r\n\r\nUnclear what the easiest way is to remove the warning from the phoebus product.\r\nAdd `--module-path` options for the modular javafx jars to the launch script?\r\nTurn everything into modules? "}

{"id":1054807251,"created_at":"2021-11-16T12:12:43Z","updated_at":"2022-05-21T22:00:30Z","state":"open","title":"Support building and running on Apple M1 Silicon","html_url":"https://github.com/bisq-network/bisq/pull/5835","body":"## Summary\r\n\r\nProblem: Prior to this commit, it was not possible to build or run (from source) the desktop app on Apple's M1 (macos aarch64) architecture.\r\n\r\nSolution: This commit makes all the changes necessary to successfully build and run on M1, but some of these changes require depending on snapshots and forks of certain dependencies, so this commit shouldn't be merged to master until those fixes are officially released. The changes made here include:\r\n\r\n1. Upgrading from JavaFX 16 to JavaFX 17. JavaFX 17 was the first release to support aarch64 binaries, and so it's required.\r\n\r\n2. Upgrading to a version of the openjfx-gradle-plugin that contains the fix at openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin#113 to download the correct aarch64-classified JavaFX 17 jars. NOTE: at the time of this commit, the fix has not been released, so we are now depending on a locally-built SNAPSHOT resolved from `mavenLocal()`.\r\n\r\n3. Upgrading to a version of the JFoenix library that includes a fix for the bug documented at sshahine/JFoenix#1187. At the time of this commit, this fix has only been published in the 'rationalityfrontline' fork of JFoenix, and so we've temporarily updated our dependency to point to that artifact. It appears that a new version of JFoenix is being developed that will contain this fix, but it hasn't shipped yet.\r\n\r\n## Notes\r\n\r\n - Gradle dependency verification metadata has been updated to reflect the changes mentioned above, but will need further updates to capture the Linux, Windows and MacOS Intel variants of the JavaFX 17 binaries.\r\n\r\n - Building and testing has been verified to work on JDKs 11 through 17, however:\r\n\r\n - Running the desktop app only works on JDKs 11 through 15 until sshahine/JFoenix#1205 is fixed. Right now, attempting to run on JDK 16+ will result in a `Cannot invoke \"javafx.scene.Node.getLayoutBounds()\" because \"this.textNode\" is null` error. See the above mentioned issue for details.\r\n\r\n - It was necessary to bump the minimum supported source compatibility in the Gradle build from Java 10 to Java 11 in order to be able to consume the upgraded JFoenix artifact.\r\n\r\n - ~~This PR builds on top of the #5824 and assumes it will be merged; only the latest commit in this PR (98dc483c10) should be considered by reviewers.~~ (no longer relevant after rebase and force-push)\r\n\r\n## TODO\r\n\r\n(what remains in order to take this PR out of draft, review and merge it)\r\n\r\n- [ ] sshahine/JFoenix#1205 to be fixed, released and upgraded to\r\n- [x] openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin#113 to be released and upgraded to\r\n- [ ] JavaFX 17 verification metadata to be updated for Linux, Windows and MacOS Intel architectures\r\n"}

{"id":1236561796,"created_at":"2022-05-16T03:20:21Z","updated_at":"2022-05-23T14:09:22Z","state":"open","title":"In RichTextFX 0.10.9， calling the `scrollToPixel` method on a CodeArea constructed in a background thread has no effect","html_url":"https://github.com/FXMisc/RichTextFX/issues/1110","body":"Here is an example:\r\n\r\n```java\r\nimport javafx.application.Application;\r\nimport javafx.application.Platform;\r\nimport javafx.scene.Scene;\r\nimport javafx.scene.layout.StackPane;\r\nimport javafx.stage.Stage;\r\nimport org.fxmisc.flowless.VirtualizedScrollPane;\r\nimport org.fxmisc.richtext.CodeArea;\r\n\r\npublic class Main extends Application {\r\n    @Override\r\n    public void start(Stage primaryStage) throws Exception {\r\n        StackPane root = new StackPane();\r\n        Scene scene = new Scene(root, 200, 400);\r\n        primaryStage.setScene(scene);\r\n\r\n        new Thread(() -> {\r\n            CodeArea area = new CodeArea();\r\n            area.replaceText(\"This is test text\\n\".repeat(10000));\r\n            area.scrollToPixel(0, 0);\r\n            Platform.runLater(() -> {\r\n                root.getChildren().add(new VirtualizedScrollPane<>(area));\r\n            });\r\n        }).start();\r\n\r\n        primaryStage.show();\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nIn RichTextFX 0.10.8, it open the `CodeArea` with the scroll bar at the top. But after updating to 0.10.9, it open the `CodeArea` with the scroll bar at the bottom.\r\n\r\nIn 0.10.9, I tried a lot of methods, but I can't create the `CodeArea` with the focus on the top in the background thread (`CodeArea`'s constructor that accepts `String` will also be at the bottom, both `selectRange` and `scrollToPixel` are invalid). The only way is to call `replaceText` on the JavaFX thread, but this will cause the screen to freeze."}

{"id":1228901575,"created_at":"2022-05-08T14:24:57Z","updated_at":"2022-05-08T14:24:57Z","state":"open","title":"SearchableComboBox : 100% cpu usage for JavaFX application thread","html_url":"https://github.com/controlsfx/controlsfx/issues/1440","body":"Hello,\r\n\r\nWhen I use the SearchableComboBox on my app, 1 core CPU is full used by the JavaFX application thread. \r\n\r\nThis problem is caused by the following code in the SearchableComboBoxSkin : \r\n\r\n    @Override\r\n    protected void layoutChildren(double x, double y, double w, double h) {\r\n        super.layoutChildren(x, y, w, h);\r\n        // ensure filteredComboBox and searchField have the same size as the field\r\n        filteredComboBox.resizeRelocate(x, y, w, h);\r\n        searchField.resizeRelocate(x, y, w, h);\r\n    }\r\n\r\nIf I comment the line **filteredComboBox.resizeRelocate(x, y, w, h);**, the problem doesn't occurs.\r\n\r\nIt seems to me that the layoutChildren method is called continuously. \r\n\r\nRegards."}

{"id":1095406013,"created_at":"2022-01-06T15:05:07Z","updated_at":"2022-04-21T04:19:18Z","state":"open","title":"GUIDE : Setup on Manjaro Linux (or Arch)","html_url":"https://github.com/travispessetto/OrigamiSMTP/issues/14","body":"If you get the error \"Error: JavaFX runtime components are missing, and are required to run this application\"\r\n\r\ninstall the package [java-openjfx](https://archlinux.org/packages/extra/x86_64/java-openjfx/)\r\n\r\nand launch the .jar with :\r\n\r\n`java --module-path /usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk/lib/javafx.controls.jar:/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk/lib/javafx.fxml.jar:/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk/lib/javafx.graphics.jar:/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk/lib/javafx.base.jar:/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk/lib/javafx.web.jar:/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk/lib/javafx.media.jar --add-modules javafx.controls,javafx.fxml,javafx.web,javafx.media -jar origami-smtp.jar`\r\n\r\nalso, be sure to use the jar from SourceForge and not the outdated one in the Releases tab of this repo\r\n"}

{"id":363955437,"created_at":"2018-09-26T10:19:30Z","updated_at":"2020-12-01T11:55:41Z","state":"open","title":"JavaFX","html_url":"https://github.com/Rails-18xx/Rails/issues/60","body":"Just a little brainstorming on my side:\r\nI believe it would be useful to change the GUI implementation to JavaFX.\r\nIn my opinion JavaFX has multiple advantages:\r\n- JavaFX is a newer framework compared to Swing/AWT, which looks more up to date and is easier to program, especially with tools like the SceneBuilder (see: https://gluonhq.com/products/scene-builder/)\r\n- JavaFX in theory should be relatively easy to port to IOS and Android (see: https://gluonhq.com/products/mobile/javafxports/)\r\n\r\nWhat do you think?"}

{"id":1001912230,"created_at":"2021-09-21T05:50:44Z","updated_at":"2021-10-08T16:58:17Z","state":"open","title":"Remove JavaFX dependency","html_url":"https://github.com/HanSolo/medusa/pull/215","body":"Fix #198 \r\n\r\nWhile using this plugin, it ignores the user specified JavaFX version and uses the one that this depends on (in this case, 16.0.1 depends on JavaFX 16).\r\n\r\nCurrently, one needs to do the following in order to use their own specific JavaFX version :\r\n\r\n```\r\n<dependency>\r\n  <groupId>eu.hansolo<\/groupId>\r\n  <artifactId>medusa<\/artifactId>\r\n  <version>16.0.1<\/version>\r\n  <exclusions>\r\n    <exclusion>\r\n      <groupId>org.openjfx<\/groupId>\r\n      <artifactId>*<\/artifactId>\r\n    <\/exclusion>\r\n  <\/exclusions>\r\n<\/dependency>\r\n```\r\n\r\n[This is the same approach used in ControlsFX](https://github.com/controlsfx/controlsfx/blob/jfx-13/mavenPublish.gradle#L63)"}

pushed. Don't do that.\r\nMay 09, 2022 7:17:52 PM com.sun.javafx.css.StyleManager loadStylesheetUnPrivileged\r\nWARNING: Resource \"\" not found.\r\n```\r\n\r\n<\/details>\r\n\r\nI don't know if `XSetErrorHandler() called with a GDK error trap pushed.` triggers any bugs in JabRef yet, but somebody must have deemed this important enough to implement some kind of warning. Just reporting what I found out so far.\r\n\r\n**Likely cause of problem:**\r\n\r\n1. Most likely the main culprit: https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8156779\r\n2. Related [discussion about this error message on stackoverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/55446534/how-to-fix-java22494-gdk-warning) points to problem with JavaFX and problems with GTK 3.\r\n3. Another [Interesting story](http://www.babelsoft.net/forum/viewtopic.php?p=27776) also points to JavaFX and problem with wayland / X11 window system\r\n    >  I finally understand what's happening. And it's indeed related to GTK3/GDK3.\r\n    > \r\n    > Negatron uses OpenJFX as its main graphical library. And OpenJFX 11+ has migrated from GTK2 to GTK3 but, with GTK3, a lot    of Linux distros have changed the graphical backend from X11 to Wayland. So, OpenJFX 11 couldn't work with those Linux distros using Wayland because OpenJFX 11 doesn't have a compatibility layer with Wayland, only with X11. To avoid having to develop a full compatibility layer with Wayland, OpenJFX 12+ simply added a hack to force GTK3 to work with X11.\r\n    > \r\n    > The thing is Negatron uses VLC to play video files. And for this to happen, the library to embed VLC within Negatron (VLCj) uses AWT, another Java graphical library. AWT can work with X11 and Wayland without issues. So, I think that AWT overrides the hack used by OpenJFX and forces the use of the newest Wayland graphical backend, screwing up OpenJFX along the way...\r\n    > \r\n    > So, I have 3 solutions at hand, sorted by increasing complexity and also from the worst to the best solution:\r\n    > 1/ completely rewrite the file chooser dialog box in pure Java, thus killing OS integration for those common dialogues in Linux,    and hope that this GTK3 issue doesn't screw anything else up.\r\n    > 2/ rewrite a part of VLCj so that it doesn't use AWT anymore.\r\n    > 3/ write the Wayland compatibility layer that nobody at OpenJFX wants to write...\r\n\r\n**Rudimentary explanation:**\r\n\r\nJabRef uses [JavaFX](https://openjfx.io/).\r\n   - JavaFX forces the usage of X11 window system.\r\n   - JavaFX is able to call GTK 3. This has been supported for a few years now and JavaFX will soon drop support for GTK 2.\r\n   - GDK (API version 3.0) uses X11 window system as default. Source: https://docs.gtk.org/gtk3/x11.html\r\n   - JavaFX and GTK employ two different error handlers.\r\n   \r\nIn some rare instances JavaFX will have to disable their error handler and at the same time for some reason, the GTK error handler could not be disabled. Then, somehow during this process an error trap is pushed but not popped. There does not seem to be an easy workaround.\r\n\r\n**Additional info:**\r\n\r\nGTKX11 error trap documentation:\r\n   - `error_trap_push`: https://docs.gtk.org/gdk3-x11/method.X11Display.error_trap_push.html\r\n   - `error_trap_pop`: https://docs.gtk.org/gdk3-x11/method.X11Display.error_trap_pop.html\r\n   - `error_trap_pop_ignored`: https://docs.gtk.org/gdk3-x11/method.X11Display.error_trap_pop_ignored.html\r\n\r\n\r\n### Appendix\r\n\r\n_No response_"}

{"id":953286165,"created_at":"2021-07-26T21:03:51Z","updated_at":"2021-08-28T03:26:28Z","state":"open","title":"Downscale JavaFX Scene Preview","html_url":"https://github.com/chunky-dev/chunky/pull/1013","body":"This takes the JavaFX preview window and downscales the preview view to fit within the JavaFX canvas sizes, thus avoiding crashes that might otherwise happen. If using fit-to-screen, there should be little to no noticeable difference on most standard scenes. Scenes that are very tall and thin, or wide and short may be downsized somewhat.\r\n\r\nMost of this was pulled out of #786. This will fix #314 and should fix #27.\r\n\r\nThis allows for renders of sizes larger than 4k on all computers without crashing (as opposed to crashing on different computers at different sizes above 4k). This makes the new effective largest size 26.7k square, or 18* 1920x1080 (34560 x19440) before crashing due to maxing out the SampleBuffer (This can be solved by replacing the double[] with a double[][], as done in #786)\r\n\r\nHere is what the canvas scale dropdown looks like now when the canvas is large enough to be scaled (previously, only had the % value on the right): \r\n  <img width=\"521\" alt=\"A screenshot showing the new Canvas Scale dropdown.\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4878558/127058124-e25aa06e-4513-46b2-a4f8-9e63d9192657.png\">"}

локальной и \"серверной\" панелей\n-настроил навигацию по файлам в обеих панелях, серверная панель работает c ограничением каталога верхнего уровня.\nБлижние планы:\n-развернуть код из урока по использованием netty)\nДальние планы:\n- подключить SqlLight, настроить в БД две таблицы (users и settings), \n- написать код для проверки логина/пароля через запрос к БД\n- написать код для ServerPanelController\nВ ресурсном файле контролера SecondaryController эти контролеры вызваются следующим образом:\n        <fx:include fx:id=\"leftPanel\" source=\"localPanel.fxml\" HBox.hgrow=\"ALWAYS\"/>\n        <fx:include fx:id=\"rightPanel\" source=\"serverPanel.fxml\" HBox.hgrow=\"ALWAYS\"/>\n\nВариант\n    @FXML\n    LocalPanelController leftPC;\n    @FXML\n    ServerPanelController rightPC;\nоказался нерабочим (leftPC и rightPC не ициализируются).\n\nОбходное решение, которое сработало:\nИнициализация с помощью кода внутри SecondaryController:\n        leftPC = (LocalPanelController) leftPanel.getUserData();\n        rightPC = (ServerPanelController) rightPanel.getUserData();\n\nи вставка в ресурсные файлы localPanel.fxml и serverPanel.fxml кода\n    <userData>\n        <fx:reference source=\"controller\" />\n    <\/userData>\n"}

{"id":1239132654,"created_at":"2022-05-17T20:37:11Z","updated_at":"2022-05-24T15:45:34Z","state":"open","title":"Virtualized Masonry Pane","html_url":"https://github.com/palexdev/MaterialFX/issues/203","body":"**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**\r\nSo I'm trying to create a sort of gallery application where a bunch of images can be viewed. However, I have been unable to find any sort of JavaFX library that provides a Masonry Pane.\r\n\r\n**Describe the solution you'd like**\r\nI would like to see a Masonry Pane. I also say [\"Virtualized\"](https://github.com/palexdev/VirtualizedFX) because, as I will explain later, the current alternative is not and therefore causes insane amounts of lag when rendering just a few images.\r\n\r\n**Describe alternatives you've considered**\r\nThe only other decent alternative I could find is the one from [JFoenix](https://github.com/sshahine/JFoenix). However that library appears to be unmaintained and and the issue with theirs is that it is not virtualized and so causes lots of issues when there are many items in the pane. Image of the JFoenix Masonry Pane is below:\r\n![687474703a2f2f6a666f656e69782e636f6d2f6769662f6d61736f6e72792e676966](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43997792/168905161-4e907cfc-a0b8-4152-8ef4-ea3d00aed354.gif)\r\n\r\nAnother alternative that I have looked at is [TilesFX](https://github.com/HanSolo/tilesfx), however that is not really a masonry pane and I have found it quite hard to work with.\r\n\r\n**Additional context**\r\nI think that something like this would be very helpful to many people since displaying images on masonry panes is very common, yet not currently possible without building a whole new node and set of tools to do it (which at least personally, I have no idea how to do). If this could be added that would be fantastic and I would much appreciate it!"}

{"id":1147706336,"created_at":"2022-02-23T07:06:35Z","updated_at":"2022-05-24T23:27:26Z","state":"open","title":"File Importer does not set some Source and Destination options when loading a template","html_url":"https://github.com/constellation-app/constellation/issues/1652","body":"<!--\r\n\r\n### Requirements\r\n\r\n* Filling out the template is required. Any pull request that does not include\r\nenough information to be reviewed in a timely manner may be closed at the\r\nmaintainers' discretion.\r\n* Have you read Constellation's Code of Conduct? By filing an issue, you are\r\nexpected to comply with it, including treating everyone with respect:\r\nhttps://github.com/constellation-app/constellation/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md\r\n\r\n-->\r\n\r\n### Prerequisites\r\n\r\n- [x] Put an X between the brackets on this line if you have done all of\r\n    the following:\r\n\r\n    -   Running the latest version of Constellation\r\n\r\n    -   Attached the ***Support Package*** via `Help` &gt;\r\n        `Support Package`\r\n\r\n    -   Checked the FAQs:\r\n        https://github.com/constellation-app/constellation/wiki/FAQ\r\n\r\n    -   Checked that your issue isn’t already filed:\r\n        https://github.com/constellation-app/constellation/issues\r\n\r\n    -   Checked that there is not already a module that provides the\r\n        described functionality:\r\n        https://github.com/constellation-app/constellation/wiki/Catalogue-of-Repositories\r\n\r\n### Description\r\nWhen loading a template,  `Destination` and `Files Include Headers` options do not set as in the template, although they are applied and ` File Parser` is trying to match for other types of files as well.\r\n\r\nE.g. \r\n1. Import a file and set the `Destination` option to `New Analytic Graph`. Then try to load a template with `destination` as `VisualSchemaFactory`. The `Destination`  field clears but when imported, a new visual graph is created as expected. The field should be displayed as  `New Visual Graph` instead of clearing. Note that this works sometimes, but can be reproduced always if the drop down is manually selected before loading the template.\r\n\r\n2. Import a file and set the `Files Include Headers`  option. Then load a template with that option set to false. It's applied in the preview (you can see it by the column headers) but the option does not set to false. If this file is now removed and a different file is imported, the option is still set but data is imported as if it was not set.  Visually setting the option should be enough to fix the problem here.\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/64826928/155273345-8fc1540e-970e-4cbe-bdb8-768a8b8d27a1.png)\r\n\r\n3. If you open a file and load a template containing a different File Parser, it still tries to load it incorrectly. I guess we should display a warning message and avoid loading.\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/64826928/155266458-66564ae9-492d-4c17-b5f9-adbc5c6ea831.png)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n### Steps to Reproduce\r\n\r\nAs above.\r\n<!--\r\n\r\n### Behaviour\r\n\r\n* Try to include measurable metrics that can be aimed for (if applicable to the issue),\r\ne.g. if it's a time issue then \"should take 5 seconds or less to finish\"\r\nor if it's a workflow issue \"should be accomplished in 2 or less clicks\".\r\n\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**Expected behaviour:** Options should display as in the template\r\n\r\n**Actual behaviour:** Options do not display as in the template\r\n\r\n**Reproduces how often:** 100%\r\n\r\n### Additional Information\r\n\r\n\r\n"}

Compile above code into a jar and run on a Windows Server 2022 using command line.\r\n2. Once UI pops up, click button on UI. The \"Hello World\" label is displayed. Console log shows \"I've been clicked!\"\r\n2. Close UI and open again using command line. Once the UI pops up, leave open overnight (or more than 12 hours).\r\n3. Click button on UI. UI hangs and label does not get displayed. Console log shows \"I've been clicked!\". {"id":1201805687,"created_at":"2022-04-12T12:51:58Z","updated_at":"2022-04-18T13:01:43Z","state":"open","title":"Using a splash screen interferes with the class loader used by JavaFX","html_url":"https://github.com/shannah/jdeploy/issues/66","body":"Our app was working perfectly fine, then I added a splash screen. After that the default class loader used by JavaFX was null. See method getDefaultClassLoader() in FXMLLoader.java. This caused our app to crash as soon as it tried to create a view via FXML. At first I thought it is caused by the short snippet used to close the splash screen (as it probably ran on the wrong thread), but even after commenting that out the app would still crash. It was only after I completely removed the splash screen from the jdeploy package that our app started working again."}

{"id":1200259138,"created_at":"2022-04-11T16:58:41Z","updated_at":"2022-05-16T08:56:18Z","state":"open","title":"Task_2_3_1","html_url":"https://github.com/Alowator/OOP/pull/8","body":"### Идея:\r\nПопробую реализовать взаимодействие игры и интерфейса через **callback'и**\r\nТо есть, по нажатию на кнопку начинается игра - создается объект `Game`, который получает наш контроллер в виде интерфейса, тогда:\r\n* Контроллер реагирует на нажатия кнопок, и дергает необходимые методы (сама игра остается независима от реализации GUI)\r\n* Игра сама сообщает котроллеру, что и когда необходимо отрисовать (логика игры инкапсулирована в саму игру, а не в GUI, что логично)\r\n\r\n### Игра:\r\n* `Game` - содержит `Grid` и `Snake`, управляет ими по команде свыше ☝\r\n* `Grid` - содержит `Cell[][]`\r\n* `Cell`- содержит еду, стены, змейку\r\n* `Snake` - содержит `List[Cell]`, основная ее задача - управлять логикой перемещения\r\n\r\n### Чего не хватает:\r\n* Реализация оставшихся объектов игры + тесты\r\n* GUI на JavaFX"}

{"id":962357811,"created_at":"2021-08-06T03:14:44Z","updated_at":"2022-03-29T07:42:29Z","state":"open","title":"Include JavaFX and Nashorn in the JAR so we're not stuck with Java 1.8 forever","html_url":"https://github.com/Innoxia/liliths-throne-public/pull/1588","body":"- What is the purpose of the pull request?\r\n\r\nFixes #1435 and #1546 (among others) and removes the need for this part of the readme:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/Innoxia/liliths-throne-public/blob/c863c6d5ad1ed625200b16791c4c707d57aa4e03/README.md#L7\r\n\r\n- Give a brief description of what you changed or added.\r\n\r\nI added the required JavaFX dependencies to pom.xml and [followed the steps](https://openjfx.io/openjfx-docs/modular#Non-Mod) needed to bundle it inside the JAR using the maven-shade plugin. JavaFX does have a bunch of native components that are OS-specific and I'm bundling Windows, Mac and Linux, so that currently bumps the JAR size from 20 MB to 120 MB. I've also replaced the Oracle JDK Nashorn with the OpenJDK version now that it's been split off into a separate library.\r\n\r\nThe few other changes I made, like adding the Launcher class were needed to get the game to run as a standalone JAR. [JavaFX doesn't like it when your main class doesn't inherit `Application`](https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8093075?focusedCommentId=13756386&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels%3Acomment-tabpanel#comment-13756386), but the dependencies bundled in your JAR can't be required by the main class directly.\r\n\r\n(for the record, I haven't done Java in a good 5 years and I have never seriously used  Maven before)\r\n\r\nThe build tutorial might need to be updated in a few places. The game can be built with a simple `mvn compile` and `mvn package` (although `mvn clean` might be needed at first if this gives you compilation errors), but I haven't tried the other suggested ways (though I would assume that those would still work for the most part, given the old main function is still there).\r\n\r\n- Are any new graphical assets required?\r\n\r\nNo\r\n\r\n- Has this change been tested? If so, mention the version number that the test was based on.\r\n\r\nNot beyond checking that it runs and skimming through the prologue with the changes.\r\n\r\n- So we have a better idea of who you are, what is your Discord Handle?\r\n\r\nI'm not currently on the Discord server.\r\n"}

{"id":1175002686,"created_at":"2022-03-21T07:50:53Z","updated_at":"2022-03-28T01:55:48Z","state":"open","title":"minimum JRE","html_url":"https://github.com/exch-bms2/beatoraja/issues/691","body":"`jdeps`と`jlink`を使い、配布JREを最小限のものにするのはどうでしょうか。\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ jdeps --list-deps --ignore-missing-deps beatoraja.jar\r\n   JDK removed internal API/com.apple.eio\r\n   JDK removed internal API/sun.reflect\r\n   java.base\r\n   java.datatransfer\r\n   java.desktop\r\n   java.logging\r\n   java.management\r\n   java.scripting\r\n   java.sql\r\n   java.xml\r\n   javafx.base\r\n   javafx.controls\r\n   javafx.fxml\r\n   javafx.graphics\r\n   jdk.unsupported\r\n```\r\n\r\n`JDK removed internal API`とあるのは無視して、また https://stackoverflow.com/questions/55439599/sslhandshakeexception-with-jlink-created-runtime により`jdk.crypto.ec`が抜けるのでこれを足して\r\n\r\n```\r\njlink --compress=2 --output jre --add-modules java.base,java.datatransfer,java.desktop,java.logging,java.management,java.scripting,java.sql,java.xml,javafx.base,javafx.controls,javafx.fxml,javafx.graphics,jdk.unsupported,jdk.crypto.ec\r\n```\r\n\r\nで`jre`ディレクトリに成果物ができます。\r\n\r\n手元の環境では、オリジナルが208MBに対し、最小版が64MBとなりました。\r\n自分で使っている限りでは特に問題は発生していません。"}

{"id":1145939144,"created_at":"2022-02-21T15:24:29Z","updated_at":"2022-02-21T22:50:58Z","state":"open","title":"Support for OpenJDK， alternative to Oracle Java.","html_url":"https://github.com/wright-cemrc-projects/corr/issues/26","body":"CorRelator depends on JavaFX, which is integrated into the official releases of Java JRE. The official Java JDK is provided by Oracle.  Oracle now requires that prior to downloading their JRE or JDK, that you register an account and accept to terms.\r\n\r\nOpenJDK (https://openjdk.java.net) is an alternative Java platform that is open-sourced and not tied to Oracle.\r\n\r\nJavaFX project is open-source and can work with OpenJDK.  The major issue is that OpenJDK does not ship this component with their installations.  We could ship a dependency of JavaFX with CorRelator, but need to avoid conflicts with any component shipping with Oracle Java.\r\n\r\nIt may be that newer Java distributions now treat JavaFX as a module, rather than an integrated part of the JDK.\r\n\r\nIf so, we could next attempt to rely on OpenJFX, the modern JavaFX equivalent, and to package a run-time distribution of the JDK and JavaFX modules required for library code. https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18547362/javafx-and-openjdk \r\n\r\nThis may be somewhat involved, and could make the distribution of CorRelator more complex rather than as a simple JAR containing CorRelator-specific code.  Next, let's investigate what would be required to support this distribution and run on OpenJDK.\r\n\r\nReferences:\r\n\r\n- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18547362/javafx-and-openjdk"}
{"id":1108580399,"created_at":"2022-01-19T21:30:46Z","updated_at":"2022-05-25T11:40:17Z","state":"open","title":"Feature Request: Progress callback","html_url":"https://github.com/vert-x3/vertx-web/issues/2113","body":"Whenever a client call is made to a long running process, like a large file upload, it would be nice to have a callback function that would retrieve the progress from the server and a way for the server code to provide progress updates. \r\nThis would be similar to what a java javafx.concurrent.Task class would to with its updateMessage and updateProgress methods. (https://docs.oracle.com/javafx/2/api/javafx/concurrent/Task.html)\r\nSimilarly, there is a framework with this feature implemented as:\r\n```\r\nFuel.post(\"/post\")\r\n    .body(/*...*/)\r\n    .requestProgress { readBytes, totalBytes ->\r\n      val progress = readBytes.toFloat() / totalBytes.toFloat() * 100\r\n      println(\"Bytes uploaded $readBytes / $totalBytes ($progress %)\")\r\n    }\r\n    .response { result -> }\r\n```\r\nFrom: https://github.com/kittinunf/fuel/tree/master/fuel\r\n\r\nStackoverflow original question: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/59269275/vert-x-webclient-progress-state/59293095#59293095"}

{"id":1003402307,"created_at":"2021-09-21T22:31:17Z","updated_at":"2022-04-20T15:06:27Z","state":"open","title":"walletfx: Refactor with AppDelegate， WalletApplication， etc.","html_url":"https://github.com/bitcoinj/bitcoinj/pull/2205","body":"* Introduce `AppDelegate` class for delegating JavaFX `Application`\r\n* Move most of existing `Main` to `WalletApplication`\r\n* `WalletTemplate` extends `WalletApplication` and specifies `\"main.fxml\"` and `\"wallet.css\"`\r\n* Create abstract class `MainWindowController` to remove remaining static global (`.instance`) references\r\n* `WalletApplication.instance()` can be used to find the active, singleton implementation/instance\r\n\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\n* All static globals are eliminated except `WalletApplication.instance()` which is more abstract and supports subclassing.\r\n* The “template” JavaFX Application main class (`Main`) is now about 30 lines of code\r\n* The “template” `WalletTemplate` (subclass of `WalletApplication`) is now about 15 lines of code\r\n* `MainController` can still be simplified but we’ll save that for a future refactoring\r\n* `Main` class allows easy switching between TestNet and MainNet (in fact it could become a command-line argument) and other configuration changes (e.g. `preferredOutputScriptType`)\r\n* Prepares the way for the next set of refactoring (making the remaining controllers more customizable)\r\n\r\nThis is a _draft_ PR because it is dependent upon PR #2204"}

{"id":321612384,"created_at":"2017-03-06T13:37:17Z","updated_at":"2022-01-25T18:13:17Z","state":"open","title":"LoadException in SceneBuilder for custom controls nested in other custom controls","html_url":"https://github.com/gluonhq/scenebuilder/issues/114","body":"Originally reported by: **A. Walter (Bitbucket: [awalterwork](https://bitbucket.org/awalterwork), GitHub: Unknown)**\n\n----------------------------------------\n\nHello,\n\nI've encountered a problem with SceneBuilder 8.3.0 and nested custom components that is similar, but NOT identical, to [Issue #60](https://bitbucket.org/gluon-oss/scenebuilder/issues/60/import-of-custom-control-reusing-other) .\n\n# Description #\n\n* Custom control OuterCustomControl that contains another custom control InnerCustomControl is not correctly imported into SceneBuilder because of a ClassNotFoundException for InnerCustomControl when OuterCustomControl's FXML OuterCustomControl.fxml is loaded in OuterCustomControl's constructor. However, SceneBuilder CAN load OuterCustomControl.fxml directly without any problems. \n\n* As a consequence, FXMLs that reference controller properties of custom control OuterCustomControl can not be opened by SceneBuilder. However, those FXMLs can be loaded and displayed in pure JavaFx code without any problems.\n\n\n# Setup to reproduce/demonstrate\n\nsee [a sample repo that demonstrates the issue](https://bitbucket.org/awalterwork/snippets2nestedcustomcontrols/src/e8dcba9dc6bc?at=master) .\n\n* a custom control InnerCustomControl that loads InnerCustomControl.fxml in its constructor.\n\n* a custom control OuterCustomControl that loads OuterCustomControl.fxml in its constructor. The FXML references InnerCustomControl.\n\n* an FXML OutermostFxml.fxml that references OuterCustomControl (extends it and references controller properties of  OuterCustomControl).\n\n* App.java demonstrates that OutermostFxml.fxml can be loaded/displayed in JavaFx code.\n\n* a JAR containing the custom controls.\n\n\n# Steps #\n* Open SceneBuilder (preferably from a terminal so we can see log messages etc.).\n\n* Import the JAR containing the custom controls. Both custom controls (InnerCustomControl and OuterCustomControl) show up in the Import dialog and can be imported, no errors or warnings are shown. [This is where this bug is different from [Issue #60](https://bitbucket.org/gluon-oss/scenebuilder/issues/60/import-of-custom-control-reusing-other), in which custom controls did not show up at all.] The JAR Analysis Report is empty. However in the terminal, we can see exceptions caused by a ClassNotFoundException for InnerCustomControl when OuterCustomControl's constructor tries to load This is an onboarding PR to help you understand and configure settings before regular Pull Requests begin.\n\n🚦 To activate Renovate, merge this Pull Request. To disable Renovate, simply close this Pull Request unmerged.\n\n\n\n---\n### Detected Package Files\n\n * `pom.xml` (maven)\n\n### Configuration Summary\n\nBased on the default config's presets, Renovate will:\n\n  - Start dependency updates only once this onboarding PR is merged\n  - Enable Renovate Dependency Dashboard creation\n  - If semantic commits detected, use semantic commit type <code>fix<\/code> for dependencies and <code>chore<\/code> for all others\n  - Ignore `node_modules`, `bower_components`, `vendor` and various test/tests directories\n  - Autodetect whether to pin dependencies or maintain ranges\n  - Rate limit PR creation to a maximum of two per hour\n  - Limit to maximum 20 open PRs at any time\n  - Group known monorepo packages together\n  - Use curated list of recommended non-monorepo package groupings\n  - Fix some problems with very old Maven commons versions\n  - Ignore spring cloud 1.x releases\n  - Ignore http4s digest-based 1.x milestones\n  - Use node versioning for @types/node\n  - Limit concurrent requests to reduce load on Repology servers until we can fix this properly, see issue 10133\n\n🔡 Would you like to change the way Renovate is upgrading your dependencies? Simply edit the `renovate.json` in this branch with your custom config and the list of Pull Requests in the \"What to Expect\" section below will be updated the next time Renovate runs.\n\n---\n\n### What to Expect\n\nWith your current configuration, Renovate will create 20 Pull Requests:\n\n<details>\n<summary>Update dependency com.jfoenix:jfoenix to v9.0.10<\/summary>\n\n  - {"id":73440993,"created_at":"2015-05-05T21:44:29Z","updated_at":"2015-05-05T21:44:29Z","state":"open","title":"create native javafx implementation","html_url":"https://github.com/hohwille/client/issues/12","body":"We decided to go for JavaFx as it is more promising than we initially thought. Besides native desktop clients it can potentially lead us into the mobile world. Further we also want to create a web implementation based on javafx that offers a bridge to the browsers DOM and to the JavaScript world. That is all we need to make it possible even though it will still be very tough. In comparison to the GWT implementation this will require the java(fx) plugin available in the browser but therefore our client code is executed a true java so we skip additional compilation and all the limitations of GWT.\n"}

{"id":462945225,"created_at":"2019-07-01T22:52:57Z","updated_at":"2019-07-01T22:53:24Z","state":"open","title":"Chapter 17. JavaFX (GUI)","html_url":"https://github.com/1027luke/thisisjava/issues/10","body":"자바 UI 변천사\r\n1. AWT(Abstract Window Toolkit)\r\n- 운영 체제가 제공하는 네이티브 UI 컴포넌트 이용\r\n- 운영 체제에 따라 UI의 모양 서로 달랐고, 종류도 제한적\r\n\r\n2. Swing\r\n- 모든 운영체제상에서 동일한 UI 갖도록 \r\n- 사용자는 애니메이션 추가된 시각적 운영 체제의 네이티브 UI 더 선호\r\n- 네이티브 UI로 보여지도록 자신의 UI 재정비\r\n- 실행 성능이 느려지고, 메모리 더 많이 사용\r\n\r\n3. JavaFX\r\n- 가볍고 풍부한 UI 제공\r\n- 레이아웃, 스타일, 애플리케이션 로직 분리 개발\r\n- 자바7 업데이트6버전부터 JavaFX2.2를 JDK와 JRE에 포함\r\n"}

{"id":1223689548,"created_at":"2022-05-03T04:45:24Z","updated_at":"2022-05-03T05:14:20Z","state":"open","title":"Upgrade to Java 17， switch to Gradle","html_url":"https://github.com/sirjonasxx/G-Earth/pull/128","body":"Currently, I have only tested the changes on MacOS. The runtime image creation for Windows still needs some work (specifically making a distinction between 32-bit and 64-bit images). \r\n\r\nThe following has been done:\r\n- uses [badass runtime plugin](https://badass-runtime-plugin.beryx.org/releases/latest/) to create platform-specific images.\r\n- switch from maven to gradle build script (kotlin)\r\n- uses [openjfx plugin](https://openjfx.io/openjfx-docs/#gradle) to obtain the required javafx modules\r\n- added G-Wasm jar to repo for now, maven link is broken for me\r\n- added g_mem_mac executable (https://github.com/dorving/g_mem_mac)\r\n- added MacOS readable icon (.icns format)\r\n- removed unused and broken imports from PortRequester.java and GEarth.java\r\n- added GEarthLauncher.java (see docs for reason)\r\n\r\nThis is still a work in progress!"}

{"id":1071497856,"created_at":"2021-12-05T16:16:48Z","updated_at":"2021-12-05T16:19:01Z","state":"open","title":"New NullPointerExceptions caused by large canvas sizes?","html_url":"https://github.com/chunky-dev/chunky/issues/1081","body":"JavaFX hardware acceleration has a maximum supported texture size defined within the graphics driver. In the past it was possible to disable hardware acceleration and use software rendering using `-Dprism.order=sw` which shifts the majority of limits towards the sample buffer which has a 12800x12800 upper limit if memory allows. {"id":754063081,"created_at":"2020-12-01T06:34:00Z","updated_at":"2020-12-01T07:21:36Z","state":"open","title":"Use JavaFX file chooser?","html_url":"https://github.com/pont-us/PuffinPlot/issues/364","body":"The Swing file chooser is not ideal: with the Mac or GTK look and feel it doesn't allow the selection of directories. The JavaFX file chooser is apparently much nicer, and it's apparently [possible to use it with Swing](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28920758/javafx-filechooser-in-swing) (see also https://github.com/veluria/NativeJFileChooser). There are some potential problems with using it, though:\r\n\r\n1. Allegedly, mixing Swing and JavaFX can get rather messy.\r\n2. It's not clear how much of JavaFX would have to be dragged in and packaged as a dependency.\r\n3. As of 2020, JavaFX (a.k.a. OpenJFX) development seems rather stagnant, and there are complaints about bugs that never get fixed. Using it may cause more problems than it solves.\r\n\r\nIn any case, users aren't actively complaining about the current file chooser, so this should be considered low priority."}

{"id":308391110,"created_at":"2018-03-25T22:13:49Z","updated_at":"2020-04-27T18:44:21Z","state":"open","title":"Graal.js and JavaFX WebView?","html_url":"https://github.com/oracle/graal/issues/326","body":"Can Graal.js replace JavaScriptCore in WebKit engine ? Or can it be used for some another abstract implementation of WebView with zero overhead during interoperation ?\r\nIt's not very interesting to use npm packets or modules on server side along with Java, because there are a lot more libraries for JVM rather than for Nodejs, i.e. everything you can do using Nodejs - you can do greatly using Java libs with performance gain (especially considering the technologies difference in age and maturity). \r\nSo, the only case i see application of Graal.js - is a dedicated \"browser\",  or some part of \"browser\".\r\n"}

{"id":566814604,"created_at":"2020-02-18T11:02:07Z","updated_at":"2021-10-05T19:21:12Z","state":"open","title":"[Modular][SDK] Multiple JavaFX jars on module path","html_url":"https://github.com/openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin/issues/71","body":"Using a combination of JavaFX SDK and dependencies on a modular HelloFX project results in multiple `javafx-controls` jars on the module path.\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n```\r\njavafx {\r\n    sdk = \"location-to-javafx-sdk-11\"\r\n    modules = [ 'javafx.controls', 'javafx.fxml' ]\r\n}\r\ndependencies {\r\n    compile 'org.controlsfx:controlsfx:11.0.1';\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe module path looks like:\r\n\r\n```\r\n--module-path \r\nhellofx/build/classes/java/main;\r\n.m2/repository/org.controlsfx/controlsfx/11.0.1/controlsfx-11.0.1.jar;\r\njavafx-sdk-11/lib/javafx.controls.jar;\r\njavafx-sdk-11/lib/javafx.fxml.jar;\r\n.m2/repository/org/openjfx/11.0.2/javafx-web-11.0.2.jar;\r\n.m2/repository/org/openjfx/javafx-controls/11.0.2/javafx-controls-11.0.2.jar;\r\n.m2/repository/org/openjfx/javafx-swing/11.0.2/javafx-swing-11.0.2.jar;\r\n.m2/repository/org/openjfx/javafx-media/11.0.2/javafx-media-11.0.2.jar;\r\n.m2/repository/org/openjfx/javafx-graphics/11.0.2/javafx-graphics-11.0.2.jar;\r\n.m2/repository/org/openjfx/javafx-base/11.0.2/javafx-base-11.0.2.jar\r\n```\r\n\r\nThere are 2 instances of `javafx-controls.jar` from the following locations:\r\n\r\n1. JavaFX SDK\r\n2. As a transitive dependency from ControlsFX"}

Under Options -> Preferences, Network, check the \"Listen for remote operation on port\" box and make sure 6050 is entered.\r\n3. Save the settings, optionally restart the application.\r\n4. Using `netstat -lpnt |grep 6050` confirm that the port is properly opened by the java process\r\n5. Attempt to open an additional copy of JabRef, either by launching the application or by using the browser extension to import a new reference.\r\n\r\nExpected behavior: based on the documentation saying \"Binding to this port makes it possible for a second JabRef instance to discover that the first one is running. In this case, unless specifically instructed to run in stand-alone mode, the second JabRef instance will pass its command line options through the port to the first JabRef instance, and then **immediately quit.**\" (emphasis added).\r\n\r\nActual behavior: When importing from the browser extension, a new instance of JabRef is opened and stays open. {"id":1202414530,"created_at":"2022-04-12T21:32:43Z","updated_at":"2022-04-12T21:32:43Z","state":"open","title":"Docker file","html_url":"https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine3/issues/667","body":"I found an example of a JavaFX app running in Docker:\r\nhttps://aboullaite.me/javafx-docker/\r\nhttps://github.com/brunoborges/fx2048\r\n\r\n```\r\nFROM gradle:jdk11 as builder\r\nCOPY --chown=gradle:gradle . /home/gradle/fxgame\r\nWORKDIR /home/gradle/fxgame\r\nRUN gradle dist --no-daemon\r\nRUN unzip /home/gradle/fxgame/build/distributions/game2048-*.zip -d /tmp/fxgame\r\n\r\nFROM ubuntu:18.04\r\nCOPY --from=builder /tmp/fxgame/image/ /fxgame\r\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install --no-install-recommends -y xorg libgl1-mesa-glx && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/* \r\nWORKDIR /fxgame\r\nCMD ./bin/fxgame\r\n```"}

There seems to be a real problem with setting the combination of CONTROL + SPACE. It doesn't work.\r\n\r\nI managed to get it working with a different key combo using:\r\n\r\n```\r\nac.setTriggerKey(KeyStroke.getKeyStroke(\"ctrl released ENTER\"));   // why won't \"ctrl pressed SPACE\" work ?\r\n```\r\n"}

{"id":767657117,"created_at":"2020-12-15T14:35:31Z","updated_at":"2021-09-20T12:22:27Z","state":"open","title":"Error launching a JavaFX application","html_url":"https://github.com/moditect/layrry/issues/67","body":"I noticed a problem when when trying to launch https://github.com/carldea/worldclock/ (from @carldea) using an external Layers config file. The problem stems form the different options there are to launch a JavaFX application. I've replicated the problem with the following code\r\n\r\n**App.java**\r\n```java\r\nimport javafx.application.Application;\r\nimport javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader;\r\nimport javafx.scene.Scene;\r\nimport javafx.scene.layout.HBox;\r\nimport javafx.stage.Stage;\r\n\r\nimport java.net.URL;\r\n\r\npublic class App extends Application {\r\n    @Override\r\n    public void start(Stage stage) throws Exception {\r\n        URL location = getClass().getResource(\"app.fxml\");\r\n        FXMLLoader fxmlLoader = new FXMLLoader(location);\r\n        HBox hbox = fxmlLoader.load();\r\n\r\n        Scene scene = new Scene(hbox);\r\n        stage.setScene(scene);\r\n        stage.setTitle(\"App\");\r\n        stage.show();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\r\n        launch();\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n**module-info.java**\r\n```java\r\nmodule app {\r\n    exports app;\r\n    requires javafx.base;\r\n    requires javafx.graphics;\r\n    requires javafx.controls;\r\n    requires javafx.fxml;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n**layers.toml**\r\n```toml\r\n[layers.javafx]\r\n    modules = [\r\n        \"org.openjfx:javafx-base:jar:{{os.detected.jfxname}}:{{javafx_version}}\",\r\n        \"org.openjfx:javafx-controls:jar:{{os.detected.jfxname}}:{{javafx_version}}\",\r\n        \"org.openjfx:javafx-graphics:jar:{{os.detected.jfxname}}:{{javafx_version}}\",\r\n        \"org.openjfx:javafx-fxml:jar:{{os.detected.jfxname}}:{{javafx_version}}\"]\r\n[layers.core]\r\n    modules = [\r\n        \"org.kordamp.ikonli:app:{{project_version}}\"]\r\n    parents = [\"javafx\"]\r\n[main]\r\n  module = \"app\"\r\n  class = \"app.App\"\r\n```\r\n\r\n**versions.properties**\r\n```java\r\nproject_version = 12.0.1-SNAPSHOT\r\njavafx_version = 11\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe error I get when running is\r\n\r\n```sh\r\nException in thread \"main\" java.lang.RuntimeException: Couldn't run module main class\r\n\tat org.moditect.layrry.internal.LayersImpl.run(LayersImpl.java:139)\r\n\tat org.moditect.layrry.Layrry.launch(Layrry.java:56)\r\n\tat org.moditect.layrry.Layrry.run(Layrry.java:50)\r\n\tat org.moditect.layrry.launcher.LayrryLauncher.launch(LayrryLauncher.java:53)\r\n\tat org.moditect.layrry.launcher.LayrryLauncher.main(LayrryLauncher.java:35)\r\nCaused by: java.lang.reflect.InvocationTargetException\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke0(Native Method)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(NativeMethodAccessorImpl.java:64)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.java:43)\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:564)\r\n\tat org.moditect.layrry.internal.LayersImpl.run(LayersImpl.java:136)\r\n\t... 4 more\r\nCaused by: java.lang.RuntimeException: java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: app.App\r\n\tat javafx.graphics/javafx.application.Application.launch(Application.java:304)\r\n\tat app@12.0.1-SNAPSHOT/app.App.main(App.java:42)\r\n\t... 9 more\r\nCaused by: java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: app.App\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.loader.BuiltinClassLoader.loadClass(BuiltinClassLoader.java:606)\r\n\tat java.base/jdk.internal.loader.ClassLoaders$AppClassLoader.loadClass(ClassLoaders.java:168)\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.ClassLoader.loadClass(ClassLoader.java:522)\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.Class.forName0(Native Method)\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.Class.forName(Class.java:468)\r\n\tat javafx.graphics/javafx.application.Application.launch(Application.java:292)\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis is caused by invoking `launch()` in the `main()` method, as shown before\r\n\r\n```java\r\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\r\n        launch();\r\n    }\r\n```\r\n\r\nHowever if the launch procedure is changed to\r\n\r\n```java\r\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\r\n        Application.launch(App.class, args);\r\n    }\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen the application class is found and launched, however it fails due to another problem related to FXML (https://github.com/moditect/layrry/issues/68). The original problem appears to be caused by different strategies involving classloaders:\r\n- `launch()` relies on the context classloader to find the target class to load, which may be different from the classloader that loaded the class with the main method to begin with.\r\n- `launch(Class, String...)` relies on same classloader as the class with the main method.\r\n\r\nI wonder if `Layrry` would have to setup the context classloader as well. I think it does not make any changes as far as I can tell."}

{"id":34134008,"created_at":"2014-05-23T00:28:50Z","updated_at":"2014-06-11T18:55:08Z","state":"open","title":"Exclude javafx dependency","html_url":"https://github.com/redfish4ktc/maven-soapui-extension-plugin/issues/125","body":"When running SmartBear 5.0.0 plugin with sun jdk6, openjdk6 or openjdk7, execution fails because of the javafx dependency cannot be resolved. See a [post](http://forum.soapui.org/viewtopic.php?f=13&t=23847) in the soapui forum that talks about this.\nIn soapui 5.0.0, this dep is declared with the system scope, see [pom of the 5.0.0 tag](https://github.com/SmartBear/soapui/blob/5.0.0/soapui/pom.xml#L546) and resolution fails because javafx is not installed with the jdk for these distributions.\nFor me, this is annoying because builds runned by CI jobs in openjdk environments failed because of that. \n\nAs mentionned by a SmartBear developer in the post, this dep is used for browsing feature only (including OAuth 2). So as not  everybody needs this, I propose to remove this dep and document that it needs to be added when declaring the plugin in a project pom when the feature is needed\n\nTasks to be peformed\n- [x] experiment integration test with\n  - [x] SmartBear implementation: locally install a \"version does not exist\" javafx jar\n  - [x] our plugin, remove the dep \n- [ ] documentation (if solution is working)\n  - [ ] workaround with SmartBear impl (cf implem or install javafx in a given directory and redeclare the javafx dep with the installation path)\n  - [ ] our plugin, when javafx dep is needed and how to add it (cf SmartBear workaround)\n"}

{"id":506520494,"created_at":"2019-10-14T08:48:37Z","updated_at":"2020-11-06T11:55:57Z","state":"open","title":"Monocle support for JavaFX 13","html_url":"https://github.com/TestFX/Monocle/issues/79","body":"Would it be possible to get a build of Monocle up from JDK 13? I'd like to use JavaFX 13, but I don't think I can run it against an older version of Monocle.\r\n\r\nAs an aside:\r\n\r\nThe readme suggests that the version of Monocle you use is tied to the version of Java you're using, but I don't think that's the case. Running JavaFX 13 on Java 11 is supported, but Monocle from OpenJDK 11 is missing methods required by JavaFX 13 (`com.sun.prims.Graphics.setPerspectiveTransform()`, for example). I think the readme should be updated to indicate that you want the version of Monocle and the version of JavaFX you're using to be in sync."}

{"id":1239774481,"created_at":"2022-05-18T10:48:10Z","updated_at":"2022-05-18T10:48:10Z","state":"open","title":"Different Launcher / Chunky JVM issues","html_url":"https://github.com/chunky-dev/chunky/issues/1264","body":"Odd issue that crops up from time to time for some reason.\r\n\r\nIt is possible to launch Chunky Launcher, via commandline (`java -jar chunkylauncher.jar`) or double clicking, and get a `Cannot find JavaFX` error while the Java Runtime is set to JVM 8. ie - `Java` is set to JVM 17 which can cause the `Cannot find JavaFX` error to occur. However you will then be met with a `Launch Error` after fixing JFX as the actual Java Runtime set within the Launcher is JVM 8.\r\n\r\nThis typically occurs if someone has previously used/attempted to use Chunky with JVM 8 and then proceeds to try JVM 17. The act of installing JVM 17 would update the default JVM and thus lead to this issue occurring.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhile I understand that having a different JVM for the Launcher and Chunky may have uses...\r\n\r\n- Do not auto populate `Java Options` with `--module-path` and `--add-modules` if the `Java Runtime` is set to JVM 8 even if the Launcher detects JVM 17 being used and finds JFX.\r\n- If a different JVM to what the Launcher is using is found in the `Java Runtime` field, query the user: `Ignore`, `Let me pick (and ignore)`, `Use Launcher JVM (and auto populate Java Options)`."}

We tried to run it on IOS on Java 9 but had issues, and since we're on Java 10/11 with JavaFX 11 right now, we're not sure where things stand.\r\n\r\nIn the hopes of speeding things up, what's the best way for us to get involved and contribute to JavaFX on mobile? It appears to me that most of the work is being done on Gluon VM, but Gluon VM is closed source?\r\n\r\nThen, from the Gluon website: \"JavaFXPorts is the open source project that brings Java and JavaFX to mobile and embedded hardware, including iPhone, iPad, Android devices, and the Raspberry Pi. JavaFXPorts can be used on its own, but it’s even better combined with Gluon Mobile.\"\r\n\r\nWhat exactly is/falls under Gluon Mobile? Is Gluon Mobile simply the Gluon Charm library? Or does Gluon VM also fall under the Gluon Mobile umbrella, and hence require a license? Is the above statement still true now that we need Gluon VM to deploy Java 9+ to mobile?\r\n"}

{"id":520774537,"created_at":"2019-11-11T06:57:20Z","updated_at":"2020-03-29T11:01:23Z","state":"open","title":"Migrating From Swing to JavaFX ?","html_url":"https://github.com/RalfBarkow/ZettelkastenFX/issues/1","body":"Robillard, Martin P., and Kaylee Kutschera. „Lessons Learned in Migrating From Swing to JavaFX“. IEEE Software, 2019, 1–1. https://doi.org/10.1109/MS.2019.2919840.\r\n\r\nAbstract:\r\nThe authors describe a case study of the migration of an interactive diagramming tool written in Java from the Swing Graphical User Interface framework to the more recent JavaFX framework. The study distills the authors’ experience identifying what information was needed to support the migration effort, and how the information was ultimately discovered. The outcome is presented in a set of five lessons about the discrepancies between expectations and reality in the search for information when migrating software between major frameworks."}

{"id":155201229,"created_at":"2016-05-17T08:17:41Z","updated_at":"2016-05-17T08:17:41Z","state":"open","title":"Javadoc til samtlige javaFx filer","html_url":"https://github.com/NielsHeltner/Webshop/issues/5","body":"Der mangler kommentarer til næsten al kode i javaFx klasserne, hvis en af os andre ønsker at rette i dem (eller tilføje funktioner) bør vi kunne danne os et indblik i hvad de enkelte klasser og metoder gør alene ved at kigge på deres javaDoc istedet for at skulle prøve og forstå hvad der sker i koden.\n\neksempel:\n\n``` java\n/**\n     * <Hvad gør dette stykke kode og hvorfor>\n     * @param product <beskrivelse af parameters formål>\n     * @param x <beskrivelse af parameters formål>\n     * @param y <beskrivelse af parameters formål>\n*/\npublic ProductItem(Product product, int x, int y) {\n        setPadding(new Insets(15, 0, 0, 0));\n        setSpacing(20);\n        setPrefWidth(130);\n        setPrefHeight(160);\n        setLayoutX(x);\n        setLayoutY(y);\n        setAlignment(Pos.TOP_CENTER);\n        setBackground(defaultBackground);\n        DropShadow ds = new DropShadow(2, new Color(0, 0, 0, 0.6));\n        ds.setSpread(0.1);\n        setEffect(ds);\n        setOnMouseEntered((MouseEvent t) -> {\n            setBorder(hoverBorder);\n        });\n        setOnMouseExited((MouseEvent t) -> {\n            setBorder(null);\n        });\n        Label text = new Label(product.getName() + \"\\n\" + product.getPrice() + \" DKK\");\n        text.setTextAlignment(TextAlignment.CENTER);\n        ImageView iv = new ImageView(new Image(\"file:icons/PHshirtIcon.png\"));\n        iv.setFitWidth(100);\n        iv.setPreserveRatio(true);\n        getChildren().addAll(iv, text);\n    }\n```\n"}

{"id":1065464497,"created_at":"2021-11-28T23:17:21Z","updated_at":"2022-01-13T06:53:29Z","state":"open","title":"Deleting an entry after Enabling/Disabling Grobid for importing metadata leads to java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException","html_url":"https://github.com/JabRef/jabref/issues/8281","body":"### JabRef version\n\nLatest development branch build (please note build date below)\n\n### Operating system\n\nWindows\n\n### Details on version and operating system\n\nJabRef 5.4--2021-11-25--7ec4c7e Windows 10 10.0 amd64  Java 16.0.2  JavaFX 17.0.1+1\n\n### Checked with the latest development build\n\n- [X] I made a backup of my libraries before testing the latest development version.\n- [X] I have tested the latest development version and the problem persists\n\n### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\n\nI found a new reliable method that triggers an java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce the behaviour:**\r\n\r\n1. Open a library with some entries\r\n2. Enable or disable `Options>preferences>Import and Export>Remote services>Allow sending pdf files and raw citation strings to a Jabref online service (Grobid) to determine Metadata. This produces better results`\r\n3. Save the change of preferences\r\n3. Delete a few entries from main table.\r\n\r\nError messages appear.\r\n\r\n**Workaround**\r\n\r\nRestarting Jabref before deleting an entry will make it so that no error messages appear.\n\n### {"id":1205582702,"created_at":"2022-04-15T13:31:49Z","updated_at":"2022-04-15T13:32:40Z","state":"open","title":"Make the updater understand multiple update site tracks","html_url":"https://github.com/imagej/imagej-updater/issues/103","body":"Different artifacts need to be served depending on:\r\n\r\n1. Major version of Java\r\n2. Stable versus unstable component versions\r\n\r\n## Major version of Java\r\n\r\nFor example, instead of https://update.imagej.net/ being the sole core ImageJ2 update site, there needs to be:\r\n\r\n* https://update.imagej.net/6/\r\n* https://update.imagej.net/8/\r\n* https://update.imagej.net/11/\r\n* https://update.imagej.net/17/\r\n\r\nFor each supported major version of OpenJDK. And the updater automatically uses the best one based on the installed version of Java.\r\n\r\nThis is complicated by JavaFX, because:\r\n\r\n* Java 6 does not support JavaFX\r\n* Java 8 has bundled JavaFX 8\r\n* Java 11+ has split JavaFX to its own project OpenJFX which you depend on like any other library (whew!)\r\n\r\nAnd unfortunately, the JavaFX API broke between JavaFX8 and JavaFX11.\r\n\r\nTherefore, for plugins like [mars-fx](https://github.com/duderstadt-lab/mars-fx) and [flimj-fx](https://github.com/flimlib/flimj-ui) currently built on JavaFX 8, we need to take care not to break them when designing this multi-track update site mechanism.\r\n\r\n## How the Updater needs to change\r\n\r\nThe Updater needs to:\r\n\r\n* Check the version of Java, and append `/<major-version>` to the update site appropriately.\r\n* Deal with the case where that particular URL prefix does not exist remotely.\r\n    * Repeatedly fall back to prior versions? E.g. if `/11` does not exist, try `/10`, `/9`, `/8`, `/7`, `/6`, ...?\r\n        * Should we include support for non-LTS versions of Java in this way? People will probably want it.\r\n        * Maybe use a `java-versions` manifest file in the root of the multi-site declaring which versions of Java have tracks?\r\n        * We could parse the directory listing but that's error prone for people who don't use Apache or don't enable indexing on their sites. Let's not.\r\n    * Or: symlink as appropriate on the server side, so that the updater never needs to fall back?\r\n* Be careful about existing update site content! It will probably need to remain in place forever, unfortunately.\r\n    * Old versions of the Updater cannot follow 301 redirects—but try testing that again just to be sure.\r\n    * For update.imagej.net, update.fiji.net, sites.imagej.net, we could maybe use hard links to duplicate the files without extra disk usage?\r\n* Give the user an informative dialog box when it detects that an update site has a newer major Java version track than it can follow, due to the locally installed version of Java being too old.\r\n\r\nImportant question: How to handle major-version-sensitive content like JavaFX plugins?\r\n* Most plugins can run under a version of Java newer than what they target. E.g. a Java-8-based plugin can run with Java 11.\r\n* But JavaFX8-based plugins won't work with JavaFX11. This is a special case; now that JavaFX11 is external, it should work e.g. with Java 17.\r\n* Other examples of major-version sensitivity: java [preview and experimental features](https://www.baeldung.com/java-preview-features). These are new features of a particular OpenJDK major version, which are subject to change in future and won't be supported in later major versions. So if a plugin wants to use them, they need to stay in one particular update site track.\r\n\r\n## Stable versus unstable\r\n\r\nTo support stable versus unstable tracks, we can lean on Maven (#104). With such a design, every update site built on a Maven artifact would automatically have stable vs unstable tracks. But how to teach the Updater to understand this? And how to name them on the remote?\r\n* `/8-stable`, `/8-unstable`, `/11-stable`, `/11-unstable`?\r\n* Nested directories?\r\n* `stable`/`unstable` versus `release`/`snapshot`?\r\n* All of these are ugly and complexify things...\r\n"}
{"id":1178024715,"created_at":"2022-03-23T12:02:23Z","updated_at":"2022-03-23T12:02:23Z","state":"open","title":"I can't compile on mac m1.","html_url":"https://github.com/andytill/erlyberly/issues/179","body":"I install java with homebrew, but getting this error\r\n....package javafx.beans.property does not exist\r\n....\r\n....hextstar/DataRow.java:[11,13] cannot find symbol\r\n  symbol:   class StringProperty\r\n  location: class hextstar.DataRow"}

{"id":435119574,"created_at":"2019-04-19T09:48:16Z","updated_at":"2019-05-20T07:01:24Z","state":"open","title":"[Tests] Add JavaFX unit tests","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipsesource/papyrus-gefx/issues/37","body":"Now that #6 is complete, we should be able to provide true unit-tests for individual parts and visuals\r\n\r\nThe plan was to use TestFX for this; however it is currently not possible due to Releng limitations.\r\n\r\nE(fx)clipse dynamically makes JavaFX available on the Module Path via JavaFX Jars shipped through a P2 Repository, which allows to use JavaFX in a very transparent manner for the end-user (He doesn't need to mess with his VM's Modules manually)\r\n\r\nHowever, the OSGi version of TestFX uses some package-imports to javafx packages, which can only be resolved by OSGi if these modules are actually available on the module path. The problem is that this isn't compatible with E(fx)'s approach, making it impossible to install TestFX (e.g. via P2).\r\n\r\nA solution might be to require having OpenJFX available at build time, and adding it explicitly on the Module Path (As expected by OSGi and TestFX). This is less flexible that E(fx)'s dynamic approach, but it would only be a requirement for developers and build servers. However, I've not tried this approach yet and I don't know if it would actually work"}
{"id":403234676,"created_at":"2019-01-25T16:40:30Z","updated_at":"2019-01-25T17:11:00Z","state":"open","title":"Add a FileSelectionBox JavaFX component","html_url":"https://github.com/PhoenicisOrg/phoenicis/issues/1805","body":"Currently we use in multiple places a file selection which consists of three components:\r\n- a label specifying what file is required (e.g. an executable or a miniature)\r\n- a textfield showing the path to the selected file\r\n- a button opening a `FileChooser` dialog\r\n\r\nBecause we use this structure in multiple places, I suggest to move this functionality to a new dedicated JavaFX component called `FileSelectionBox` (or something similar)."}
{"id":397404404,"created_at":"2019-01-09T14:49:01Z","updated_at":"2019-01-20T10:22:38Z","state":"open","title":"Improve JavaFX component package structure","html_url":"https://github.com/PhoenicisOrg/phoenicis/issues/1752","body":"Currently our JavaFX component classes are located inside packages with the following naming scheme: `org/phoenicis/javafx/components/.../(control/skin/behavior)`.\r\nFor example is the `ApplicationSidebar` class located in `org/phoenicis/javafx/components/application/control` and the `SearchBoxSkin` class located in `org/phoenicis/javafx/components/common/skin`.\r\n\r\nThis package structure leads to the creation of a lot of nested `control`, `skin` and `behavior` packages, which makes the orientation inside the `components` package quite hard in my opinion.\r\nThis is especially the case if the next the `control`, `skin` and `behavior` packages also an additional `utils` package exists.\r\n\r\nTherefore I suggest we simplify our JavaFX component package structure to the following scheme:\r\n- controls: `components/control/...`\r\n- skins: `components/skin/...`\r\n- behaviors: `components/behavior/...`\r\n- utils: `components/utils/...`, alternatively we could also add the utility classes for our JavaFX components to the `components/control/...` package\r\n\r\nWhat do you think?"}

{"id":1099965953,"created_at":"2022-01-12T07:18:53Z","updated_at":"2022-05-09T21:14:51Z","state":"open","title":"Vast Memory Consumption on Ubuntu 20.04","html_url":"https://github.com/JabRef/jabref/issues/8416","body":"### JabRef version\r\n\r\n5.4 (latest release)\r\n\r\n### Operating system\r\n\r\nGNU / Linux\r\n\r\n### Details on version and operating system\r\n\r\nUbuntu 20.04.3 with Gnome Shell 3.36.8 on Wayland\r\n\r\n### Checked with the latest development build\r\n\r\n- [ ] I made a backup of my libraries before testing the latest development version.\r\n- [X] I have tested the latest development version and the problem persists\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n\r\nWhen opening JabRef and loading a library or creating a new one, memory consumption starts to increase quickly and continues until Memory and Swap are filled up. The first time this occurred to me, I had to force restart my PC. I think the second time the operating system force closed JabRef, at least it just closed once Memory and Swap were entirely filled. \r\n\r\nSystem Monitor does not associate the huge memory consumption (+6 GB) with JabRef. On the processes tab it lists JabRef as consuming 1.3 GB of memory. The remaining additional memory consumption doesn't show up in the process list at all. \r\n\r\nI am only having such memory issues when using JabRef. Every other program I use works like a charm (e.g. Firefox, PyCharm, Thunderbird, Texmaker, Spotify and others).\r\n\r\n## Steps to reproduce\r\n1. Open JabRef\r\n2. Open any Library\r\n\r\nSecond option:\r\n1. Open JabRef\r\n2. Create a new library\r\n3. This would allow fxml elements to have their value bound to those held in the ModelAdapter. Values in the view would then be updated automatically without having to rely on each controller to request new values every time a ModelEvent is caught.  "}
