{"id":711301716,"created_at":"2020-09-29T17:09:44Z","updated_at":"2020-11-25T01:18:51Z","state":"open","title":"JavaFX bean support (need contributions to happen)","html_url":"https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-databind/issues/2865","body":"**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**\r\nI want to directly serialize and deserialize JavaFX beans\r\nWhat is JavaFX bean? Simply it's like a regular pojo, but fields are wrapped in a special class. This wrapper adds ability to listen to field changes. It supports collections, maps, regular objects, primitives, etc.\r\n\r\n**Describe the solution you'd like**\r\nSpecial serializer and deserializer that handles wrapping and unwrapping of fields\r\n\r\n**Usage example**\r\nDirectly mapping JavaFX checkboxes and text fields to a config class and then save it using jackson\r\n\r\n**Additional context**\r\nRelevant wrapper classes can be found here: https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.openjfx/javafx-base\r\nExample JavaBean:\r\n```java\r\npublic class SimpleModel {\r\n    private final StringProperty name = new SimpleStringProperty();\r\n    private final ObjectProperty<CustomObject> something = new SimpleObjectProperty();\r\n\r\n    public String getName() {\r\n        return name.get();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public StringProperty nameProperty() {\r\n        return name;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public void setName(String name) {\r\n        this.name.set(name);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public String getSomething() {\r\n        return something.get();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public StringProperty somethingProperty() {\r\n        return name;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    public void setSomething(String something) {\r\n        this.something.set(something);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```"}

{"id":604500635,"created_at":"2020-04-22T06:47:35Z","updated_at":"2020-05-28T05:45:07Z","state":"open","title":"JavaFX glitchy rendering on Linux","html_url":"https://github.com/caprica/vlcj-javafx-demo/issues/31","body":"This is IMO a problem with JavaFX on Linux, but I am documenting here for reference.\r\n\r\nWith simple Scenes this will not be apparent, but there are two cases where glitchy flickering rendering occurs, especially with complex scenes or especially when putting the scene graph under \"stress\" I suppose, e.g. by rendering many video views at the same time.\r\n\r\n1. Resizing causes all sorts of bad rendering, especially with e.g. menus in the top part of a border pane. The resizing/repositioning of the menu bar will badly lag the resizing of the frame, leading to the menu bar being out of position until it catches up and looking pretty ugly.\r\n\r\n2. Flickering/leaking of the background scene fill - here it looks like some race condition or some other sort of thread synchronisation issue which becomes apparent the more you add to a scene (the glitching appears to happen on later components rather than earlier ones, or the busier the scene gets (e.g. I render a grid of 2x2 or more concurrent video views). These glitches are really bad.\r\n\r\nThe stranger thing about #2 is that sometimes when you run the application it will be flawless. Other times when you run the exact same application (e.g. immediately after, without making any changes) the glitches will occur. Once your application runs it seems either locked in to a glitching or non glitching state.\r\n\r\nThis page documents some flags that can be used that may help:\r\n\r\nhttp://werner.yellowcouch.org/log/javafx-8-command-line-options/\r\n\r\n1. -Dprism.forceUploadingPainter=true (it is false by default) for the menu glitch\r\n2. -Dprism.dirtyopts=false (it is true by default) for the other glitches\r\n\r\nIn my own tests, #2 so far has fixed the second glitching/flickering case, but it will come with a performance penalty. The conclusion here is the \"dirty optimisations\" that JavaFX is doing, on Linux at least, are broken in some way.\r\n\r\nWhen I tested on macOS I did not see these problems, but my macOS testing is less extensive.\r\n\r\nI do not routinely test on any Microsoft platform."}

{"id":1094507197,"created_at":"2022-01-05T16:03:37Z","updated_at":"2022-03-09T20:48:14Z","state":"open","title":"fix: Added workaround for JDK-8205915. Will fix issues #221， #263 and #306.","html_url":"https://github.com/gluonhq/scenebuilder/pull/427","body":"To avoid the issue filed in JDK-8205915, for MacOS the call to `TextInputControl.paste()` method is replaced with a class `com.oracle.javafx.scenebuilder.app.util.TextInputControlPaster`. This utility class prevents the controls paste method if desired and directly writes the Clipboard contents into the correct position of the TextInputControl. \r\n\r\nThis does not fix the root cause for JDK-8205915 but ensures that the paste functionaliy can be used in Scene Builder on MacOS. Once JDK-8205915 is solved, this workaround shall be removed.\r\n\r\n### Issue\r\nWhen pasting clipboard contents into TextInputControl elements, then the clipboard contents is always pasted twice on MacOS. There is a bug ticket for JavaFX in JBS, which is JDK-8205915.\r\n\r\nAs this behavior is very annoying on MacOS, this PR might provide a temporary workaround until JDK-8205915 is fixed.\r\n\r\n<!--- The issue this PR addresses -->\r\nFixes #221\r\nFixes #263\r\nFixes #306\r\n\r\n### Progress\r\n\r\n- [x] Change must not contain extraneous whitespace\r\n- [x] License header year is updated, if required\r\n- [x] Verify the contributor has signed [Gluon Individual Contributor License Agreement (CLA)](https://docs.google.com/forms/d/16aoFTmzs8lZTfiyrEm8YgMqMYaGQl0J8wA0VJE2LCCY)"}

{"id":1213691916,"created_at":"2022-04-24T15:54:17Z","updated_at":"2022-04-24T15:54:17Z","state":"open","title":"Catch and warn on \"com.sun.prism.RTTexture.createGraphics()\" because \"\" is null","html_url":"https://github.com/chunky-dev/chunky/issues/1245","body":"`java.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke \"com.sun.prism.RTTexture.createGraphics()\" because \"\" is null` occurs if you increase Canvas size and it exceeds the maximum texture size, in conjunction with the UI elements, supported by JavaFX.\r\n\r\nIdeally we need to catch and warn on this. Doing so would mean we could default to `-Dprism.order=hw`/`d3d` and boost UI responsiveness with the warning prompting users to try `-Dprism.order=sw` if they need to bypass the maximum texture size."}

{"id":281033999,"created_at":"2017-12-11T14:24:05Z","updated_at":"2017-12-12T08:23:09Z","state":"open","title":"[WIP] Move to Java 9","html_url":"https://github.com/JabRef/org.jabref.gui.customjfx.support/pull/1","body":"One part of getting JabRef compatible with Java 9 and the module system (see https://github.com/JabRef/jabref/pull/3421 ) is getting this library ready for Java 9.\r\n\r\nThis might seem straight-forward, but I am hitting some road bumps. The required modules and exports are quickly specified, but two classes we use `com.sun.javafx.collections.ObservableListWrapper` and `com.sun.javafx.scene.input.ExtendedInputMethodRequests` are not exported by the respective JavaFX modules, which means we can't use them in a Java 9 build.\r\n\r\nI am not sure how to best get around this restriction."}

{"id":993964358,"created_at":"2021-09-11T22:38:23Z","updated_at":"2022-04-10T03:28:00Z","state":"open","title":"plugin downloads wrong architecture for macOS M1","html_url":"https://github.com/openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin/issues/112","body":"I'm running on macOS with a Silicon (M1) chip.\r\n\r\nI set the version in the plugin to 17, which should download openjfx 17, which has M1 support.\r\n\r\nWhen I run my application, I get the following error:\r\n\r\n```\r\nLoading library prism_es2 from resource failed: java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: /Users/vewert/.openjfx/cache/17/libprism_es2.dylib: dlopen(/Users/vewert/.openjfx/cache/17/libprism_es2.dylib, 1): no suitable image found.  Did find:\r\n\t/Users/vewert/.openjfx/cache/17/libprism_es2.dylib: mach-o, but wrong architecture\r\n\t/Users/vewert/.openjfx/cache/17/libprism_es2.dylib: stat() failed with errno=38\r\n```\r\n\r\nI checked `/Users/vewert/.openjfx/cache/17/` and ran `file libprism_es2.dylib` and got: `libprism_es2.dylib: Mach-O 64-bit dynamically linked shared library x86_64` which makes it look like it has downloaded the Intel libraries instead of the M1 libraries.\r\n\r\nI'm not sure if the problem is that the M1 version isn't available on Maven Central, or the plugin is downloading the wrong one.\r\n\r\nAs a work around, I downloaded the JavaFX 17 jdk, set a local sdk: https://github.com/openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin#5-using-a-local-javafx-sdk\r\n"}
{"id":115956084,"created_at":"2015-11-09T20:14:08Z","updated_at":"2021-08-04T10:40:55Z","state":"open","title":"ClassNotFoundException when cloning JavaFX's SimpleListProperty","html_url":"https://github.com/kostaskougios/cloning/issues/45","body":"I'm trying to clone a class I have that uses the [`SimpleListProperty`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/api/javafx/beans/property/SimpleListProperty.html) class from JavaFX 8. But for some reason it's not playing along. I tried finding the cause my self but I kind of got lost in all the cloning logic.\n\nCan you think of any reason why this would fail?\n\n``` java\npublic class CloneTest {\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Cloner cloner = new Cloner();\n\n        Data myData = new Data();\n        myData.slp.add(\"Hello\");\n\n        SimpleListProperty<Object> simpleListProp = new SimpleListProperty<>();\n        simpleListProp.set(myData.slp);\n\n        // Exception here\n        Data clonedData = cloner.deepClone(myData);\n\n        myData.slp.set(0, \"World\");\n\n        System.out.println(myData.slp.get(0));\n        System.out.println(clonedData.slp.get(0));\n    }\n\n    public static class Data {\n        SimpleListProperty<Object> slp = new SimpleListProperty<>(FXCollections.observableArrayList());\n    }\n\n}\n```\n"}

{"id":406243866,"created_at":"2019-02-04T09:31:32Z","updated_at":"2021-11-11T09:21:36Z","state":"open","title":"Remove classifier from JavaFX artifacts when publishing to Maven Central","html_url":"https://github.com/openjfx/javafx-gradle-plugin/issues/26","body":"The JavaFX gradle plugin applies the required platform-dependent classifier to any JavaFX module included in a project.\r\n\r\nBut if this project is being published with the `maven` plugin, this plugin generates a `pom` file based on the existing dependencies. Since the JavaFX ones include the classifier, this classifier will go to the pom. In other words, the pom will have a JavaFX dependency with a classifier based on the platform from where it was published.\r\n\r\nIf later on this library is consumed in a different platform, artifacts for both platforms will be added, causing a possible conflict due to split package.\r\n\r\nTo avoid this issue, the JavaFX gradle plugin could add a task to remove the classifier in case the maven plugin is used.\r\n\r\n\r\n"}
